In this article, we discussed the belongings of thermal and solutal stratification for mixed convection Oldroyd-B nanomaterial flow generated by an unsteady bi-directionally expandable surface. The effect of chemical reaction is also included. Moreover, temperature and concentration at the surface and far away from the surface are adjusted through predefined surface temperature, which is not reported earlier. The major outcomes are bulleted below:
Temperature and concentration curves are showing negative tendencies for larger amounts of heat distribution indices r,s.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left(r,s\right).$$\end{document}
Larger amount of unsteadiness S\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$S$$\end{document} is generating low temperature as well as low nanoparticles concentration.
The behavior of both temperature and concentration distributions are qualitative similar for large amounts of Deborah numbers (β1,β2)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$({\beta }_{1},{\beta }_{2})$$\end{document}.
Thermal thickness of boundary layer has a negative tendency for nanomaterial constraints β1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\beta }_{1}$$\end{document} and β2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\beta }_{2}$$\end{document}.
Solutal stratification constraint ε2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\varepsilon }_{2}$$\end{document} provides an enhancement in concentration profile and its related wideness of boundary layer.
Thermal stratification constraint ε1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\varepsilon }_{1}$$\end{document} provides a reduction in temperature profile and its related thermal wideness of boundary layer.
Rate of heat transference is improved with the escalation in the amounts of unsteady factor, solutal stratification constraint and heat distribution indices.
Rate of mass transference is developed with the intensification in the amounts of thermal stratification constraint, unsteady constraint and heat distribution indices.Finally, it is anticipated that this technical exploration will not only deliver useful information to its reader but also will be helpful for industrial and engineering applications, like, coating a sheet with nanomaterial, improvement of the photo-conversion efficiency, production processes of rubber hydrochloride and polyvinyl films, etc. It is stated that this parametric study will be beneficial for upcoming researchers working in this field because of its variety of applications in engineering sectors.

